of them, but they come

00:06:13.070 --> 00:06:15.990
back with a more general
solution or a proposal to get

00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:17.250
something better done, right?

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:17.610
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:06:17.610 --> 00:06:18.630
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: There's
generalization going on.

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:19.030
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:06:19.030 --> 00:06:20.230
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And that
should be rewarded.

00:06:20.230 --> 00:06:21.120
And that should be encouraged.

00:06:21.120 --> 00:06:21.450
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:06:21.450 --> 00:06:24.050
An example is if you're a forest
ranger, they send you

00:06:24.050 --> 00:06:26.605
out in the forest to cut
down the diseased tree.

00:06:26.605 --> 00:06:29.410
The novice forest ranger is
going to go in, cut down the

00:06:29.410 --> 00:06:31.730
diseased tree, and come back
and say, I'm done sir.

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:33.900
