00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:30.160
do this, and you just
go ahead and do it.

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:31.750
It's about not being
a doormat.

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:33.880
It's about challenging the
status quo and trying to think

00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:35.970
of better ways of making
things happen.

00:07:35.970 --> 00:07:36.920
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Absolutely.

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:39.760
Part of that also is just
learning to communicate well.

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:42.170
This is something I know
that does not come

00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:43.680
naturally to everybody.

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:45.765
There's that old joke about how
do you know if an engineer

00:07:45.765 --> 00:07:46.560
is outgoing?

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:47.410
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: How, Ben?

00:07:47.410 --> 00:07:49.310
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Looks
at your shoes.

00:07:49.310 --> 00:07:49.565
All right.

00:07:49.565 --> 00:07:50.570
Fine.

00:07:50.570 --> 00:07:50.910
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
Ooh, tough crowd.

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:53.640
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So, but
communication is critical on a

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:56.860
team when you're doing software
engineering because

00:07:56.860 --> 00:07:59.250
you want to let your manager
and your teammates know.

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:00.120
You want to know about your

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:01.960
victories, about your failures.

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:03.810
You want to know what your
expectations are.

00:08:03.810 --> 00:08:05.220
What do you need, right?

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:05.420
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:06.560
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Having the
answer to that question

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:09.490
ready to go when somebody asks
you instead of just sitting

00:08:09.490 --> 00:08:11.780
there with the blinders on
doing what you're told.

00:08:11.780 --> 00:08:13.590
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And
obstacles, even.

00:08:13.590 --> 00:08:14.460
Like--

00:08:14.460 --> 00:08:14.660
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Sure.

00:08:14.660 --> 00:08:16.600
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Remember when
your team had some issues

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:19.160
with legal, and they were like
six weeks waiting for a

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:19.990
response from legal.

00:08:19.990 --> 00:08:22.040
And Ben and I were having a cup
of coffee, and it's like,

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:23.920
oh my God, you know, this
is just killing us.

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:25.480
This legal is not responding.

00:08:25.480 --> 00:08:26.900
And I said, why didn't
you tell me.

00:08:26.900 --> 00:08:28.470
I know these people in legal.

00:08:28.470 --> 00:08:30.330
And I got on the phone and
resolved it in about an hour

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:31.200
and a half.

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:33.200
And that's not because I'm
some amazing person.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:37.250
It's just because I knew who to
call and talk to politely,

00:08:37.250 --> 00:08:38.080
let's shall we say.

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:38.700
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
All because I

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:40.020
communicated with you.

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:40.450
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:08:40.450 --> 00:08:40.850
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Awesome.

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:42.870
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Yay
communication.

00:08:42.870 --> 00:08:45.730
So another thing that people
often forget about in big

00:08:45.730 --> 00:08:51.230
companies is actually is that
people treat you the way that

00:08:51.230 --> 00:08:55.500
you ask to be treated,
I guess, is the way--

00:08:55.500 --> 00:08:55.710
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:08:55.710 --> 00:08:57.560
If you expect somebody to
act a certain way, they

00:08:57.560 --> 00:08:58.390
often act that way.

00:08:58.390 --> 00:08:58.760
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:08:58.760 --> 00:08:59.500
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:03.940
So, it's about getting
your work done.

00:09:03.940 --> 00:09:05.740
Nobody should be counting how
many minutes you're at your

00:09:05.740 --> 00:09:08.150
desk when you check
in or check out.

00:09:08.150 --> 00:09:09.660
If you get your work
done, it's obvious.

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:11.730
If you don't get your work
done, it's obvious.

00:09:11.730 --> 00:09:12.250
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:09:12.250 --> 00:09:13.620
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So that's
what we mean by-- and it

00:09:13.620 --> 00:09:14.630
certainly is true at Google.

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:16.200
One of the reasons we like
working there is they treat

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:17.930
everybody like an adult
by default.

00:09:17.930 --> 00:09:19.090
And it's a wonderful thing.

00:09:19.090 --> 00:09:21.780
And that is not true of other
companies I have been in.

00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:21.990
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:09:21.990 --> 00:09:24.510
Well, there was a guy that came
to work with us, and he

00:09:24.510 --> 00:09:26.340
was on my team a number
of years ago.

00:09:26.340 --> 00:09:28.590
And he'd worked in industry
for 20 years.

00:09:28.590 --> 00:09:30.380
And it was his first day.

00:09:30.380 --> 00:09:32.060
You're a little bit,
like, overwhelmed.

00:09:32.060 --> 00:09:33.470
Quarter to 5:00, he came
up to me and said,

00:09:33.470 --> 00:09:34.900
look, I'm really sorry.

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:36.460
I have an appointment that
I couldn't move.

00:09:36.460 --> 00:09:37.030
I've got to go.

00:09:37.030 --> 00:09:39.680
But I'll be here 15 minutes
later tomorrow.

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:42.790
And I said, look, man, I don't
care when you come and go.

00:09:42.790 --> 00:09:44.760
As long as you put in your 80
hours a week, you'll be fine.

00:09:47.530 --> 00:09:50.170
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Fitz is just cruel.

00:09:50.170 --> 00:09:52.590
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And he looked
at me and he understood

00:09:52.590 --> 00:09:53.820
that I was joking.

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:57.160
But he did get the point that
he's responsible for making

00:09:57.160 --> 00:10:00.430
things happen, and that it's not
about being in a seat at a

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:00.940
certain time.

00:10:00.940 --> 00:10:03.780
It's about being available to
your team to make sure that

00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:04.550
the work gets done.

00:10:04.550 --> 00:10:04.790
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Sure.

00:10:04.790 --> 00:10:08.470
You were telling me another time
when we do a conference

00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:12.420
in Chicago every winter where
we rent out a big hall at a

00:10:12.420 --> 00:10:14.760
university, a whole
building in fact.

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:17.740
And one of the first times you
went there, you went there to

00:10:17.740 --> 00:10:21.270
get the keys from the person
who runs the building.

00:10:21.270 --> 00:10:24.380
And instead of a series of
lectures about don't do this,

00:10:24.380 --> 00:10:25.850
don't go here, blah, blah, blah,
stay out of blah, blah,

00:10:25.850 --> 00:10:28.690
blah, the guy was just like,
here's the building.

00:10:28.690 --> 00:10:30.130
Here are the keys.

00:10:30.130 --> 00:10:31.930
I'll get them from
you on Monday.

00:10:31.930 --> 00:10:32.170
See you.

00:10:32.170 --> 00:10:34.570
And like, you were telling
me that was--

00:10:34.570 --> 00:10:35.050
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: That
was intimidating.

00:10:35.050 --> 00:10:35.550
It was really.

00:10:35.550 --> 00:10:36.070
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: It was
intimidating because it's

00:10:36.070 --> 00:10:38.880
like, wow, this person just
put so much trust in me.

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:41.440
I better leave this place better
then I found it, right.

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:45.030
They expect me to behave this
way, so I'm going to live up

00:10:45.030 --> 00:10:45.690
to their expectations.

00:10:45.690 --> 00:10:46.420
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:10:46.420 --> 00:10:48.100
I mean, if they set up
this fence and they

00:10:48.100 --> 00:10:49.010
say, here's the fence.

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:49.770
It's six feet tall.

00:10:49.770 --> 00:10:50.390
It's made out of concrete.

00:10:50.390 --> 00:10:52.090
Don't go any further
than that.

00:10:52.090 --> 00:10:54.550
People will often just pile
crap up against the fence

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:57.020
because they're like, I'm being
treated like a child and

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:57.870
I'm going to act like one.

00:10:57.870 --> 00:10:58.970
I'm a caged animal.

00:10:58.970 --> 00:11:01.270
I'm going to run around
and rattle the cage.

00:11:01.270 --> 00:11:02.550
People look for those
boundaries.

00:11:02.550 --> 00:11:04.290
But when there are no boundaries
and you're given

00:11:04.290 --> 00:11:08.660
this responsibility, I think
it's a great responsibility.

00:11:08.660 --> 00:11:09.890
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:11:09.890 --> 00:11:11.200
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: So let's talk
about another thing is

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:12.920
taking risks.

00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:16.230
If you're in a company, in an
organization where you are

00:11:16.230 --> 00:11:20.800
allowed to take risks and to
expand your comfort zone, you

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:22.520
can do things like fail fast.

00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:26.590
You can take more
responsibility.

00:11:26.590 --> 00:11:30.590
You can fail, document what
you've learned, adapt, and

00:11:30.590 --> 00:11:33.620
then try again.

00:11:33.620 --> 00:11:35.490
If somebody gets upset with
failure, just explain to them

00:11:35.490 --> 00:11:37.800
it's a way of learning
really quickly.

00:11:37.800 --> 00:11:38.300
Think about,

00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:40.500
Think about-- anybody
here have kids?

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:42.310
You can raise your hand.

00:11:42.310 --> 00:11:45.650
You ever see a kid burn
themself on the stove?

00:11:45.650 --> 00:11:47.540
It's painful for the kid,
but you know what?

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:50.590
They learn really fast
that that's hot.

00:11:50.590 --> 00:11:50.690
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
So does my cat.

00:11:50.690 --> 00:11:51.670
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And they
don't want to touch that.

00:11:51.670 --> 00:11:53.060
You can sit there and give
them a lecture on

00:11:53.060 --> 00:11:54.730
thermodynamics and
all you want.

00:11:54.730 --> 00:11:57.030
But, man, they just stick their
hand in there and that's

00:11:57.030 --> 00:11:59.135
the last time they're ever
going to pull that stunt.

00:11:59.135 --> 00:11:59.630
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:11:59.630 --> 00:12:01.200
Also when you exercise,
that's one of the

00:12:01.200 --> 00:12:02.770
things they talk about.

00:12:02.770 --> 00:12:05.530
If you work out at a gym,
sometimes you want to do

00:12:05.530 --> 00:12:07.710
weights to the point where your
muscles actually start to

00:12:07.710 --> 00:12:10.175
fail because that's the point
where you improve.

00:12:10.175 --> 00:12:12.910
If you always just do just
enough exercise so that it's

00:12:12.910 --> 00:12:14.370
comfortable and then you
walk away, you never

00:12:14.370 --> 00:12:15.510
really get any better.

00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:17.460
You just stay at that
level, right.

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:19.600
If you exercise to failure, you
start to push yourself.

00:12:19.600 --> 00:12:20.990
You grow, you adapt.

00:12:20.990 --> 00:12:21.860
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
Right, right.

00:12:21.860 --> 00:12:23.760
So without that risk, you
really never improve.

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:24.150
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:12:24.150 --> 00:12:26.420
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: So, those are
a few of the tips that you

00:12:26.420 --> 00:12:29.190
can do if you're living in a
lovely garden that's well

00:12:29.190 --> 00:12:31.320
raked like this.

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:35.020
Unfortunately, we're aware that
most companies look a lot

00:12:35.020 --> 00:12:39.920
more like this kind
of a garden.

00:12:39.920 --> 00:12:42.880
And most people work
for people who

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:46.570
look more like this.

00:12:46.570 --> 00:12:47.330
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:12:47.330 --> 00:12:49.240
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: So let's talk
a little bit about the

00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:51.520
bad manager which is--

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:52.380
there's a statistic--

00:12:52.380 --> 00:12:55.210
and remember that 75% of all
statistics are made up--

00:12:55.210 --> 00:12:58.980
there's a statistic that 50% of
the happiness of your job

00:12:58.980 --> 00:13:01.740
comes from your manager, whether
you're happy working

00:13:01.740 --> 00:13:03.310
with them or working for them.

00:13:03.310 --> 00:13:06.430
And that really is true
in my experience.

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:09.340
I've had the, I'd say,
opportunity to work for some

00:13:09.340 --> 00:13:12.105
really great managers in my
time, not only at Google but

00:13:12.105 --> 00:13:12.940
in other places.

00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:15.930
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So, a
typical bad manager is someone

00:13:15.930 --> 00:13:17.600
who essentially prevents
a lot of the things

00:13:17.600 --> 00:13:18.930
we just talked about.

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:21.160
They prevent you from taking
any risks at all.

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:22.510
Failure is a terrible thing.

00:13:22.510 --> 00:13:25.920
Not even the smallest failure is
terrifying to the manager.

00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:27.500
And of course, that spills
over to you.

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:30.580
And then you're afraid to
take any risks, as well.

00:13:30.580 --> 00:13:33.630
In addition, the manager also
thinks that you're there to

00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:35.230
serve him or her.

00:13:35.230 --> 00:13:38.370
And again, instead of what can
I do for you, it's what have

00:13:38.370 --> 00:13:39.730
you done for me lately.

00:13:39.730 --> 00:13:41.800
So, all the meetings you
have are sort of

00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:43.190
you're on the defensive.

00:13:43.190 --> 00:13:46.460
You're always trying to prove
that you have a value to him

00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:47.350
or to the company.

00:13:47.350 --> 00:13:47.725
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:13:47.725 --> 00:13:50.380
How are you gonna help me climb
the ladder because I'm

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:51.260
the manager here.

00:13:51.260 --> 00:13:51.560
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:13:51.560 --> 00:13:52.940
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And whatever
you do, I'm gonna

00:13:52.940 --> 00:13:53.680
take credit for it.

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:54.280
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Nasty.

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:55.300
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Unless
you screw up, in which

00:13:55.300 --> 00:13:56.590
case that's all you.

00:13:56.590 --> 00:13:59.800
And that's unfortunately
how it works.

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:03.020
And this is something that most
people don't talk about,

00:14:03.020 --> 00:14:05.830
but everyone's aware of on the
team, is that the bad manager

00:14:05.830 --> 00:14:09.730
will ignore people like this,
low performers on the team.

00:14:09.730 --> 00:14:11.830
And that is one of the
worst things that a

00:14:11.830 --> 00:14:12.790
bad manager can do.

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:14.170
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well, it's
a huge drag on the team.

00:14:14.170 --> 00:14:15.525
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Well, it
destroys the team's morale.

00:14:15.525 --> 00:14:15.940
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:17.490
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: It causes
you to lose your best

00:14:17.490 --> 00:14:18.060
performers.

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:21.230
But, I mean, you've got six good
guys on your team and one

00:14:21.230 --> 00:14:22.770
person like this.

00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:24.035
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And pretty
soon, your best people

00:14:24.035 --> 00:14:25.790
on the team start to leave--

00:14:25.790 --> 00:14:27.000
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Because they
get tired of dragging

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:28.830
this person along.

00:14:28.830 --> 00:14:31.740
So a good manager's someone
who's really going to take

00:14:31.740 --> 00:14:34.950
care of low performers.

00:14:34.950 --> 00:14:37.120
So this is some of the things
that a bad manager might do.

00:14:37.120 --> 00:14:37.910
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Other characters.

00:14:37.910 --> 00:14:38.890
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Others
characters.

00:14:38.890 --> 00:14:42.510
Another important person to be
very wary of is the office

00:14:42.510 --> 00:14:44.290
politician.

00:14:44.290 --> 00:14:44.980
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
He's awesome.

00:14:44.980 --> 00:14:46.390
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: This is
a very friendly person.

00:14:46.390 --> 00:14:48.790
They're usually very great
at managing up.

00:14:48.790 --> 00:14:50.280
And this isn't necessarily
a manager.

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:52.370
This might be another engineer
on your team.

00:14:52.370 --> 00:14:54.500
They're very quick to
take credit for

00:14:54.500 --> 00:14:55.780
something that happens.

00:14:55.780 --> 00:14:58.180
They're also very quick
to assign blame.

00:14:58.180 --> 00:15:02.120
But they put a lot of energy
into looking impactful, but

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:03.410
not being impactful.

00:15:03.410 --> 00:15:05.070
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Perception
is 9/10 of the law.

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:05.440
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Exactly.

00:15:05.440 --> 00:15:06.730
Perception is 9/10 of the law.

00:15:06.730 --> 00:15:07.830
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And
they understand that.

00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:10.660
And they do everything to make
their perception as important

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:11.660
as possible.

00:15:11.660 --> 00:15:14.100
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And the thing
that most engineers will

00:15:14.100 --> 00:15:16.380
do when they encounter someone
like this is they'll just go

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:18.820
heads down and ignore them
and say, I'm going

00:15:18.820 --> 00:15:19.630
to write great code.

00:15:19.630 --> 00:15:20.610
I'm going to have
a great product.

00:15:20.610 --> 00:15:21.650
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Engineers
hate politics.

00:15:21.650 --> 00:15:23.420
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: 'Cause I
don't like the politics, and I

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:25.660
don't want to deal
with this person.

00:15:25.660 --> 00:15:29.320
But that's very dangerous
because if you're not careful,

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:31.540
this person can wind up getting
promoted and being

00:15:31.540 --> 00:15:32.750
your manager.

00:15:32.750 --> 00:15:34.690
We've seen that happen, too.

00:15:34.690 --> 00:15:36.420
So they're someone
to steer around.

00:15:36.420 --> 00:15:40.140
But it's another example of
why even if you don't like

00:15:40.140 --> 00:15:43.040
dealing with the promotion
process or stuff like that,

00:15:43.040 --> 00:15:44.650
it's important to pay attention
to that sort of

00:15:44.650 --> 00:15:46.640
thing because it's
a way of getting

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:48.230
yourself in a safe place.

00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:48.740
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: You
don't want to get run

00:15:48.740 --> 00:15:49.643
over by this person.

00:15:49.643 --> 00:15:50.530
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
Right, exactly.

