They put so much energy into
being so passionate about

00:23:40.410 --> 00:23:42.460
everything that they end up
getting almost nothing done

00:23:42.460 --> 00:23:44.250
because they're not choosing
their battles.

00:23:44.250 --> 00:23:46.300
And it tends to drag down the
momentum of the team.

00:23:46.300 --> 00:23:49.310
It tends to drag down momentum
of the leader of the team,

00:23:49.310 --> 00:23:52.880
having to defend and deal with
everything that's happening.

00:23:52.880 --> 00:23:56.880
So, you need to know not only
just which battles to choose.

00:23:56.880 --> 00:23:59.330
You need to understand what
kind of political capital

00:23:59.330 --> 00:24:02.100
you're spending to win
a certain battle.

00:24:02.100 --> 00:24:02.840
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
Is it worth it?

00:24:02.840 --> 00:24:03.810
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Is it worth it?

00:24:03.810 --> 00:24:06.020
Are you gonna spend all your
capital over here or are you

00:24:06.020 --> 00:24:06.780
gonna spend it over here?

00:24:06.780 --> 00:24:08.530
Because once you've used it
up-- you've called in your

00:24:08.530 --> 00:24:10.440
favors, you've done whatever--

00:24:10.440 --> 00:24:13.200
you can't just turn around and
have another screaming battle

00:24:13.200 --> 00:24:15.050
the next day on a different
subject.

00:24:15.050 --> 00:24:16.750
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Because if
you think of it as a train and

00:24:16.750 --> 00:24:18.890
you're trying to stop every
engineer that comes by every

00:24:18.890 --> 00:24:21.270
15 minutes in the train,
eventually they're just gonna

00:24:21.270 --> 00:24:22.630
run you right over.

00:24:22.630 --> 00:24:23.860
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And
lose their patience.

00:24:23.860 --> 00:24:24.900
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: They
lose their patience.

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:26.800
But also remember that every
time people hit the brakes,

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:28.990
you're slowing down the progress
of the product.

00:24:28.990 --> 00:24:32.170
So that's something that you
really got to be careful and

00:24:32.170 --> 00:24:33.420
think about, is it worth it?

00:24:36.690 --> 00:24:38.160
If you're gonna beg forgiveness
rather than ask

00:24:38.160 --> 00:24:39.850
permission, make sure it's
for the right thing.

00:24:39.850 --> 00:24:43.180
You don't want to spend all
your political capital in

00:24:43.180 --> 00:24:45.110
making t-shirts or something.

00:24:45.110 --> 00:24:47.810
You'd be better to spend it
on launching a product--

00:24:47.810 --> 00:24:50.110
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Now
sometimes you have a really

00:24:50.110 --> 00:24:53.280
great idea but you're not sure
how to communicate it upwards

00:24:53.280 --> 00:24:56.250
in the organization or laterally
to other teams.

00:24:56.250 --> 00:24:59.340
And you'll fight a battle, and
you'll scream about it.

00:24:59.340 --> 00:25:01.950
And it turns out sometimes the
best way to get your idea out

00:25:01.950 --> 00:25:04.780
there is not to make a giant
stink about it, but instead to

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:09.580
do the subtle, subliminal way of
moving the message around.

00:25:09.580 --> 00:25:12.300
So it turns out that your ideas
can go really, really

00:25:12.300 --> 00:25:13.570
far in a company--

00:25:13.570 --> 00:25:13.970
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Really far.

00:25:13.970 --> 00:25:15.580
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: --if you
don't take the credit for it,

00:25:15.580 --> 00:25:17.170
or if you just don't care
whether you get

00:25:17.170 --> 00:25:18.370
credit for the idea.

00:25:18.370 --> 00:25:20.710
So it can be something as
simple, at the grassroots

00:25:20.710 --> 00:25:24.460
level, just sort of whispering
this idea to certain friends

00:25:24.460 --> 00:25:26.080
or to certain people
on another team

00:25:26.080 --> 00:25:27.100
at the lunch table.

00:25:27.100 --> 00:25:31.410
Or mention it in passing when
a VP is walking by.

00:25:31.410 --> 00:25:33.580
And maybe he'll overhear.

00:25:33.580 --> 00:25:35.500
It's an art form in
itself, but it's

00:25:35.500 --> 00:25:36.420
actually pretty powerful.

00:25:36.420 --> 00:25:38.600
We've seen this happen,
right, where an idea--

00:25:38.600 --> 00:25:41.090
and by the time maybe somebody
at the top who is a decision

00:25:41.090 --> 00:25:43.940
maker hears the idea formally
presented, there's been so

00:25:43.940 --> 00:25:47.280
much buzz about it already in
the company that it doesn't

00:25:47.280 --> 00:25:48.040
seem like such a crazy idea.

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:49.350
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And you can
actively use this if you're

00:25:49.350 --> 00:25:51.680
trying to change someone's mind
in your organization, is

00:25:51.680 --> 00:25:55.930
tell people that you know who
trust you that they trust and

00:25:55.930 --> 00:25:58.180
ask them to mention the
idea to that person.

00:25:58.180 --> 00:26:00.510
And if they hear it from
[INAUDIBLE], even if they know

00:26:00.510 --> 00:26:03.300
what's going on, if they keep
hearing this over and over

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:04.670
again, they're gonna
be like, hey.

00:26:04.670 --> 00:26:07.550
And next thing you know, you
hear it coming out of some

00:26:07.550 --> 00:26:10.160
vice president's mouth at a
press conference or something.

00:26:10.160 --> 00:26:12.780
And your response can be,
hey, that's my idea.

00:26:12.780 --> 00:26:14.460
Or you can be like, hey,
that's my idea.

00:26:14.460 --> 00:26:16.080
That's pretty awesome.

00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:16.410
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:26:16.410 --> 00:26:16.720
Yeah.

00:26:16.720 --> 00:26:17.450
What's more important?

00:26:17.450 --> 00:26:19.215
That it happens or that
you get the credit?

00:26:19.215 --> 00:26:19.680
Sometimes you have to choose.

00:26:19.680 --> 00:26:20.550
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: You're
choosing, right.

00:26:20.550 --> 00:26:22.360
You have to choose sometimes.

00:26:22.360 --> 00:26:26.170
So, let's talk about habits.

00:26:26.170 --> 00:26:28.990
Anyone here has ever attempted
to quit something, like quit

00:26:28.990 --> 00:26:31.310
smoking, quit drinking?

00:26:31.310 --> 00:26:31.920
Some people I know--

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:32.040
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Caffeine.

00:26:32.040 --> 00:26:32.870
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: --have
to quit eating.

00:26:32.870 --> 00:26:34.170
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Have
to quit eating.

00:26:34.170 --> 00:26:36.600
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: But bad
habits, or systems, really

00:26:36.600 --> 00:26:38.080
can't be destroyed.

00:26:38.080 --> 00:26:41.560
But we found that they can be
replaced by a new habit.

00:26:41.560 --> 00:26:42.180
OK.

00:26:42.180 --> 00:26:44.070
You have a great example of this
you did with one of the

00:26:44.070 --> 00:26:45.005
teams you work with.

00:26:45.005 --> 00:26:45.280
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:26:45.280 --> 00:26:46.750
We had--

00:26:46.750 --> 00:26:50.640
one of the teams I took over, at
least for awhile, had this

00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:51.490
standing meeting.

00:26:51.490 --> 00:26:53.850
I know it was Agile Scrum
something something something.

00:26:53.850 --> 00:26:54.325
But--

00:26:54.325 --> 00:26:55.860
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
It was Agile--

00:26:55.860 --> 00:26:56.530
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Oh, OK.

00:26:56.530 --> 00:26:57.085
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
--at one point.

00:26:57.085 --> 00:26:57.350
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:26:57.350 --> 00:26:59.280
I'm not trained in those
magic techniques.

00:26:59.280 --> 00:27:00.970
But it was every morning.

00:27:00.970 --> 00:27:03.535
We're gonna all stand here for
20 minutes or whatever and go

00:27:03.535 --> 00:27:04.910
around in a circle,
blah, blah, blah.

00:27:04.910 --> 00:27:06.980
And people were kind of
frustrated with it, but they

00:27:06.980 --> 00:27:08.310
were just doing it
out of habit.

00:27:08.310 --> 00:27:09.280
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Well, but it
turned into an hour, right?

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:09.590
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Got worse.

00:27:09.590 --> 00:27:11.460
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: There was
sitting down, and it was like

00:27:11.460 --> 00:27:13.180
group therapy.

00:27:13.180 --> 00:27:13.650
Well, you know, I went out--

00:27:13.650 --> 00:27:13.850
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Not so efficient.

00:27:13.850 --> 00:27:15.090
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
--last night.

00:27:15.090 --> 00:27:15.310
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:27:15.310 --> 00:27:16.480
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: You know, I
don't have anything really to

00:27:16.480 --> 00:27:19.080
say but I want to talk about
Rails, you know.

00:27:19.080 --> 00:27:21.460
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
But the thing is--

00:27:21.460 --> 00:27:21.790
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Ow.

00:27:21.790 --> 00:27:22.370
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: It's cool.

00:27:22.370 --> 00:27:22.890
It's cool.

00:27:22.890 --> 00:27:24.470
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Oh, oh, stop.

00:27:24.470 --> 00:27:27.770
But the point is it wasn't a
totally useless meeting.

00:27:27.770 --> 00:27:29.210
There were some nuggets of

00:27:29.210 --> 00:27:30.860
communication going on in there.

00:27:30.860 --> 00:27:33.170
So it would not have been,
probably, that smart to just

00:27:33.170 --> 00:27:34.090
be like, this is stupid.

00:27:34.090 --> 00:27:35.060
Kill this meeting forever.

00:27:35.060 --> 00:27:36.200
Go away.

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:37.600
Instead, we just replaced it.

00:27:37.600 --> 00:27:40.580
We said, all right, let's
instead have just an email

00:27:40.580 --> 00:27:41.930
thread that goes out
every morning.

00:27:41.930 --> 00:27:44.890
You have a cron job that just
sends an email saying, hey,

00:27:44.890 --> 00:27:45.930
what's going on?

00:27:45.930 --> 00:27:46.980
What did you do yesterday?

00:27:46.980 --> 00:27:48.600
What are you blocked on today?

00:27:48.600 --> 00:27:50.470
Everybody reply to this
thread, right.

00:27:50.470 --> 00:27:52.810
Everybody spends 30
seconds replying.

00:27:52.810 --> 00:27:53.380
You're done.

00:27:53.380 --> 00:27:55.510
People can read the thread
whenever they want.

00:27:55.510 --> 00:27:56.610
So much more efficient.

00:27:56.610 --> 00:27:59.110
Gets the exact same sort
of thing done.

00:27:59.110 --> 00:28:00.990
And it sparks off side
conversations, which is all

00:28:00.990 --> 00:28:02.070
that matters.

00:28:02.070 --> 00:28:02.620
That's we wanted.

00:28:02.620 --> 00:28:05.040
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: But there's
one sneaky thing you did as

00:28:05.040 --> 00:28:07.890
well in that, is that-- and this
is a sneaky technique for

00:28:07.890 --> 00:28:10.380
introducing anything new
or changing anything--

00:28:10.380 --> 00:28:13.780
is three magic words,
let's try this.

00:28:13.780 --> 00:28:15.960
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
We can always undo.

00:28:15.960 --> 00:28:16.710
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Let's
try this for 30 days.

00:28:16.710 --> 00:28:17.950
Let's try this for two weeks.

00:28:17.950 --> 00:28:18.620
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:28:18.620 --> 00:28:19.825
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: If it doesn't
work, everybody hates

00:28:19.825 --> 00:28:21.000
it, we'll go back.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:25.560
And oftentimes, people are like,
oh my God, I mean, it's

00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:26.210
not permanent.

00:28:26.210 --> 00:28:27.670
We can actually just try
something for 30 days.

00:28:27.670 --> 00:28:27.920
OK.

00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:29.790
And then after three weeks,
they're like, oh,

00:28:29.790 --> 00:28:31.080
it wasn't so bad.

00:28:31.080 --> 00:28:31.270
This isn't so--

00:28:31.270 --> 00:28:32.935
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Or they
just forget it was a trial and

00:28:32.935 --> 00:28:33.650
just do it forever.

00:28:33.650 --> 00:28:39.130
That's usually what happens
if it goes well.

00:28:39.130 --> 00:28:41.090
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And beyond
that, let's talk about-- back

00:28:41.090 --> 00:28:44.305
to the organization
and moving around.

00:28:44.305 --> 00:28:46.580
This is something that most
engineers we know-- and it's

00:28:46.580 --> 00:28:49.390
often been abhorrent to
us, I think, as well--

00:28:49.390 --> 00:28:51.850
is the ladder of a company.

00:28:51.850 --> 00:28:53.130
OK.

00:28:53.130 --> 00:28:55.480
We talked earlier about the
office politician who's always

00:28:55.480 --> 00:28:57.660
sort of working it, trying
to go up the ladder.

00:28:57.660 --> 00:29:00.780
And most of these bad
companies, bad

00:29:00.780 --> 00:29:03.520
organizations, have--

00:29:03.520 --> 00:29:05.590
there's a mismatch between doing
the right thing for the

00:29:05.590 --> 00:29:08.380
company and doing the right
thing to promoted.

00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:08.780
OK.

00:29:08.780 --> 00:29:10.030
So you have to make a choice.

00:29:10.030 --> 00:29:11.430
And it doesn't have to
be black or white.

00:29:11.430 --> 00:29:12.930
It can be a little bit
of a gray blend.

00:29:12.930 --> 00:29:14.440
You can do a little
bit of both.

00:29:14.440 --> 00:29:17.690
But it's dangerous if you choose
to always do the right

00:29:17.690 --> 00:29:20.700
thing and ignore
being promoted.

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:21.540
OK.

00:29:21.540 --> 00:29:24.540
So, as we mentioned earlier, you
should climb this ladder

00:29:24.540 --> 00:29:25.820
until you get to a safe place.

00:29:25.820 --> 00:29:28.200
And so, it is worthwhile to
spend energy on that.

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:29.060
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: This
works particularly in

00:29:29.060 --> 00:29:32.070
companies that are very power
driven, that where hierarchy

00:29:32.070 --> 00:29:35.000
and title is right at the
forefront of everybody's mind.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.500
That if you can get yourself
up to a high title, then

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:40.200
people will leave you alone
because you've got power,

00:29:40.200 --> 00:29:44.240
right, or some imaginary
title that tells people

00:29:44.240 --> 00:29:45.230
to leave you alone.

00:29:45.230 --> 00:29:46.850
Just working the
system, right?

00:29:46.850 --> 00:29:47.510
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:29:47.510 --> 00:29:48.420
It's your bubble.

00:29:48.420 --> 00:29:49.550
It's your safe haven.

00:29:49.550 --> 00:29:52.530
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Now a
companion to that idea is not

00:29:52.530 --> 00:29:54.700
only can you work up the ladder
to the point where

00:29:54.700 --> 00:29:57.380
nobody can tell you what to do,
you can go find some place

00:29:57.380 --> 00:29:58.250
in the company to hide.

00:29:58.250 --> 00:30:01.180
It sounds crazy, but
there are projects

00:30:01.180 --> 00:30:02.430
that don't get bothered.

00:30:02.430 --> 00:30:05.540
There are teams that have so
much credibility that no one

00:30:05.540 --> 00:30:08.080
will question or bug you, or
just give you a bunch of

00:30:08.080 --> 00:30:09.040
freedom that you might
not have otherwise.

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:10.660
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: There's often
an executive who values

00:30:10.660 --> 00:30:13.220
what you're doing, as well, more
than some other executive

00:30:13.220 --> 00:30:15.210
that might be in a different
part of the company.

00:30:15.210 --> 00:30:17.280
So moving to a different
department or different team

00:30:17.280 --> 00:30:21.300
or something is often a good
way of being safe when the

00:30:21.300 --> 00:30:22.320
nuclear war comes.

00:30:22.320 --> 00:30:23.380
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Sometimes
you have to do this every

00:30:23.380 --> 00:30:25.480
couple years as the company
changes if you

00:30:25.480 --> 00:30:27.300
want to stay happy.

00:30:27.300 --> 00:30:29.410
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Some of us
have been in companies that

00:30:29.410 --> 00:30:31.680
every fifth Thursday
is layoff Thursday.

00:30:31.680 --> 00:30:35.200
I worked at a company years ago
that I will not name and

00:30:35.200 --> 00:30:36.755
nobody answered the
phone on Thursday.

00:30:39.425 --> 00:30:42.480
And if your boss showed up in
your office all a sudden, it

00:30:42.480 --> 00:30:43.710
was just panic time.

00:30:43.710 --> 00:30:45.760
But--

00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:46.710
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Talk
about perception.

00:30:46.710 --> 00:30:47.300
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
Perception, yeah.

00:30:47.300 --> 00:30:48.570
Upward perception.

00:30:48.570 --> 00:30:49.620
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: This
is a tricky thing.

00:30:49.620 --> 00:30:52.730
We said earlier that perception
is 9/10 of the law.

00:30:52.730 --> 00:30:56.190
And so what that really means
is being aware not just of

00:30:56.190 --> 00:30:58.340
getting stuff done and doing the
right thing, but always be

00:30:58.340 --> 00:31:00.690
thinking in the back of your
head, how does this look to

00:31:00.690 --> 00:31:04.190
people not on my team or
people above my level?

00:31:04.190 --> 00:31:05.930
What are they perceiving, right,
because that is at

00:31:05.930 --> 00:31:08.210
least as important as what
you're actually doing.

00:31:08.210 --> 00:31:10.290
The office politician
knows this.

00:31:10.290 --> 00:31:12.260
And you need to at least--

00:31:12.260 --> 00:31:14.290
maybe you don't need to
manipulate people the way the

00:31:14.290 --> 00:31:16.140
office politician does, but at
least you need to be aware of

00:31:16.140 --> 00:31:18.840
it and make sure it is not
misrepresenting what you're

00:31:18.840 --> 00:31:19.590
actually doing.

00:31:19.590 --> 00:31:19.860
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:31:19.860 --> 00:31:21.830
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So, you
want to launch things as much

00:31:21.830 --> 00:31:24.080
as possible because that creates
a great perception.

00:31:24.080 --> 00:31:25.510
You want to under-promise.

00:31:25.510 --> 00:31:27.110
You want to over-deliver.

00:31:27.110 --> 00:31:29.100
These are all things
we strive for.

00:31:29.100 --> 00:31:31.960
And I personally, I had problems
with this when I

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:34.580
first became a manager,
a leader.

00:31:34.580 --> 00:31:37.160
My team had the project
[INAUDIBLE], we had a huge

00:31:37.160 --> 00:31:40.960
amount of technical debt, and
it was just crushing us.

00:31:40.960 --> 00:31:43.630
So the first thing I said was,
all right guys, I'm the new

00:31:43.630 --> 00:31:44.470
leader here.

00:31:44.470 --> 00:31:47.360
We really need to hunker down
and spend the next six or nine

00:31:47.360 --> 00:31:49.950
months just focusing on our
technical debt so that we can

00:31:49.950 --> 00:31:51.990
be free of these shackles
and then move on.

00:31:51.990 --> 00:31:53.190
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And
your director said--

00:31:53.190 --> 00:31:53.340
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:31:53.340 --> 00:31:53.670
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Great idea.

00:31:53.670 --> 00:31:53.880
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
The director was

00:31:53.880 --> 00:31:54.570
like, that's great.

00:31:54.570 --> 00:31:54.940
We love it.

00:31:54.940 --> 00:31:55.980
You should totally do that.

00:31:55.980 --> 00:31:57.980
Of course, he was completely
wrong.

00:31:57.980 --> 00:31:58.650
He didn't actually--

00:31:58.650 --> 00:31:59.400
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
He wasn't lying.

00:31:59.400 --> 00:32:00.540
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well, he
