00:39:39.270 --> 00:39:40.655
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: There's
an immense amount of power

00:39:40.655 --> 00:39:41.170
that flows--

00:39:41.170 --> 00:39:42.990
I mean, there's like the
official org chart.

00:39:42.990 --> 00:39:44.650
Then there's the real
chart of power.

00:39:44.650 --> 00:39:47.260
And administrative assistants
are right in there, way more

00:39:47.260 --> 00:39:48.270
powerful than you think.

00:39:48.270 --> 00:39:49.540
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Well, a good
administrative assistant

00:39:49.540 --> 00:39:53.210
will wield their executive's
power and--

00:39:53.210 --> 00:39:54.070
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
As a proxy.

00:39:54.070 --> 00:39:55.430
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Sometimes for
good, sometimes for bad.

00:39:55.430 --> 00:39:55.940
But, yeah.

00:39:55.940 --> 00:39:58.520
So you don't want to be on
the wrong side of that.

00:39:58.520 --> 00:39:59.030
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Great.

00:39:59.030 --> 00:40:02.110
So, the other thing, just
talking just about in terms of

00:40:02.110 --> 00:40:05.150
communicating with people, a
lot of people love to do

00:40:05.150 --> 00:40:06.760
electronic communication.

00:40:06.760 --> 00:40:07.780
You're gonna do email.

00:40:07.780 --> 00:40:09.110
You're gonna do chat rooms.

00:40:09.110 --> 00:40:09.770
You're gonna do instant
messages.

00:40:09.770 --> 00:40:11.080
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
Hangouts on air--

00:40:11.080 --> 00:40:11.770
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Hang [? outside ?]

00:40:11.770 --> 00:40:12.400
[? air. ?]

00:40:12.400 --> 00:40:15.510
Face time is a huge deal.

00:40:15.510 --> 00:40:18.000
The mere act of getting on a
plane and flying to the other

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:20.600
branch of your company, or just
driving to wherever the

00:40:20.600 --> 00:40:21.670
other office is--

00:40:21.670 --> 00:40:25.070
being in somebody's face has a
massive impact, not just on

00:40:25.070 --> 00:40:27.020
the ability to get things done,
just in the connection

00:40:27.020 --> 00:40:29.650
you make with that person.

00:40:29.650 --> 00:40:32.150
10 minutes in the face of an
executive, or whoever, is

00:40:32.150 --> 00:40:34.160
gonna have a much more memorable
connection to that

00:40:34.160 --> 00:40:37.130
person than 20 emails you
have over two weeks.

00:40:37.130 --> 00:40:37.840
It's not the same.

00:40:37.840 --> 00:40:40.450
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: I learned
this lesson.

00:40:40.450 --> 00:40:44.900
I've known this for years, but I
decided to take a shortcut a

00:40:44.900 --> 00:40:45.540
few months ago.

00:40:45.540 --> 00:40:47.380
I had a meeting with a senior
vice president.

00:40:47.380 --> 00:40:48.320
It's a 15 minute meeting.

00:40:48.320 --> 00:40:49.870
I wasn't gonna fly
out to Mountain

00:40:49.870 --> 00:40:51.260
View for that or anything.

00:40:51.260 --> 00:40:55.960
And we had a global outage of
our video conferencing system.

00:40:55.960 --> 00:40:59.700
And so then I backed off to
Google Voice, which was out.

00:40:59.700 --> 00:41:01.932
So, I'm in my cell phone,
kneeling down in the corner of

00:41:01.932 --> 00:41:03.950
our building trying to get a
signal with my one hand in my

00:41:03.950 --> 00:41:06.060
ear and my phone up
against my head.

00:41:06.060 --> 00:41:07.090
And they can't hear.

00:41:07.090 --> 00:41:09.210
They heard every third word.

00:41:09.210 --> 00:41:12.100
So, that's a very
extreme example.

00:41:12.100 --> 00:41:16.550
But being there, being there
face-to-face, in person, is

00:41:16.550 --> 00:41:21.000
not only more helpful in the
room, but where it helps is

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:24.410
coming into the room and going
out of the room You've got

00:41:24.410 --> 00:41:24.730
little more time.

00:41:24.730 --> 00:41:25.780
Hey, how was your weekend?

00:41:25.780 --> 00:41:26.290
What did you do?

00:41:26.290 --> 00:41:27.080
What's going on?

00:41:27.080 --> 00:41:29.200
You wind up with chance
encounters in the hallway.

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:31.170
You might walk to the next
meeting with this person, get

00:41:31.170 --> 00:41:32.040
a few extra minutes.

00:41:32.040 --> 00:41:33.890
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:41:33.890 --> 00:41:35.060
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: It's another
reason why we talk

00:41:35.060 --> 00:41:36.970
about how it's so important
for teams

00:41:36.970 --> 00:41:38.760
to have lunch together.

00:41:38.760 --> 00:41:41.560
We give tours of our
office in Chicago.

00:41:41.560 --> 00:41:43.050
And we show them the
cafe where you get

00:41:43.050 --> 00:41:44.050
free lunch for Google.

00:41:44.050 --> 00:41:46.150
And a lot of people will say,
I don't know how Google can

00:41:46.150 --> 00:41:47.060
afford this?

00:41:47.060 --> 00:41:49.590
And the answer is, how can
Google not afford this.

00:41:49.590 --> 00:41:50.405
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Return
on investment.

00:41:50.405 --> 00:41:51.270
It's so great.

00:41:51.270 --> 00:41:53.790
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: It's huge
to get your teams--

00:41:53.790 --> 00:41:55.610
even if they're not talking
about your product-- get

00:41:55.610 --> 00:41:56.850
people together for lunch.

00:41:56.850 --> 00:41:58.620
Get them to understand that
they're working with other

00:41:58.620 --> 00:42:01.180
human beings that have lives,
that have wives

00:42:01.180 --> 00:42:02.665
and children, perhaps.

00:42:02.665 --> 00:42:04.180
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Absolutely.

00:42:04.180 --> 00:42:06.440
Sometimes when you're trying to
do electronic communication

00:42:06.440 --> 00:42:08.040
with people, they
don't respond or

00:42:08.040 --> 00:42:09.810
they're too busy, right.

00:42:09.810 --> 00:42:12.190
It's amazing when you just
pop your face over

00:42:12.190 --> 00:42:13.930
at their desk or--

00:42:13.930 --> 00:42:14.450
this is crazy.

00:42:14.450 --> 00:42:16.450
Sometimes we pick up the phone,
and we call their desk.

00:42:16.450 --> 00:42:18.330
And they jump because they're
like, what's that thing

00:42:18.330 --> 00:42:19.220
ringing on my desk.

00:42:19.220 --> 00:42:20.740
I forgot it was there.

00:42:20.740 --> 00:42:21.970
What is that for?

00:42:21.970 --> 00:42:24.840
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: How many
engineers hate the phone?

00:42:24.840 --> 00:42:26.600
I don't even have a phone
on my desk anymore.

00:42:26.600 --> 00:42:28.540
It rings through Gmail,
which is kind of cool.

00:42:28.540 --> 00:42:31.140
But even when that rings,
I'm like what is that?

00:42:31.140 --> 00:42:33.820
I prefer the asynchronous
communication.

00:42:33.820 --> 00:42:35.220
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So,
there is a trick.

00:42:35.220 --> 00:42:39.220
Sometimes you need to
communicate with executives.

00:42:39.220 --> 00:42:41.320
Something's important enough
that you actually need to get

00:42:41.320 --> 00:42:43.750
in front of them and ask
them for something.

00:42:43.750 --> 00:42:46.180
And there is an anti-pattern and
there's a pattern here we

00:42:46.180 --> 00:42:47.380
want to promote.

00:42:47.380 --> 00:42:49.490
The anti-pattern is to--

00:42:49.490 --> 00:42:50.860
maybe you're not right in
front of their face.

00:42:50.860 --> 00:42:52.960
Maybe you just want
to send an email.

00:42:52.960 --> 00:42:56.350
And the anti-pattern is you go
in and you write this long

00:42:56.350 --> 00:42:58.280
rant, this tirade about
something's

00:42:58.280 --> 00:42:58.990
wrong, blah, blah, blah.

00:42:58.990 --> 00:42:59.280
This is wrong.

00:42:59.280 --> 00:43:00.510
Then I did this and this--

00:43:00.510 --> 00:43:02.550
And it's 15 paragraphs long--

00:43:02.550 --> 00:43:03.390
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
No line breaks.

00:43:03.390 --> 00:43:05.250
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
No line---

00:43:05.250 --> 00:43:05.920
and all sorts of--

00:43:05.920 --> 00:43:06.670
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Because
this is your chance.

00:43:06.670 --> 00:43:08.040
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: All sorts
of questions in there,

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:09.580
embedded in there, right.

00:43:09.580 --> 00:43:11.445
And what does an executive
do when they get

00:43:11.445 --> 00:43:12.150
an email like that?

00:43:12.150 --> 00:43:12.500
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Delete.

00:43:12.500 --> 00:43:12.790
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:43:12.790 --> 00:43:14.190
Now why do they do that?

00:43:14.190 --> 00:43:15.760
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Because they
just don't have time to

00:43:15.760 --> 00:43:16.300
understand it.

00:43:16.300 --> 00:43:17.990
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:43:17.990 --> 00:43:19.480
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: A busy
executive gets about 10

00:43:19.480 --> 00:43:20.370
seconds to go through email.

00:43:20.370 --> 00:43:24.900
If any of you have ever seen an
exec's inbox, it looks like

00:43:24.900 --> 00:43:28.650
a distributed denial
of service.

00:43:28.650 --> 00:43:31.625
Because the emails just come,
and they come from everywhere.

00:43:31.625 --> 00:43:32.350
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:43:32.350 --> 00:43:34.380
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And so, you
get about 10 seconds of their

00:43:34.380 --> 00:43:35.770
time before they timeout.

00:43:35.770 --> 00:43:38.180
So if they get 10 seconds into
your first paragraph and

00:43:38.180 --> 00:43:42.000
you're on bullet point one of
612 and they can't figure out

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:43.625
the point, they're just
gonna delete it.

00:43:43.625 --> 00:43:45.870
I wish I could help this guy,
just don't have time.

00:43:45.870 --> 00:43:49.570
And people, like Ben said, will
usually rant forever.

00:43:49.570 --> 00:43:51.100
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So, we have
a technique that we think

00:43:51.100 --> 00:43:52.670
works pretty well, has
worked for us.

00:43:52.670 --> 00:43:55.620
We call it the three bullets
and a call to action.

00:43:55.620 --> 00:44:00.450
So essentially, you make three
short bullet points, one

00:44:00.450 --> 00:44:02.580
sentence each if possible.

00:44:02.580 --> 00:44:04.000
We love this example.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:06.380
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: This
is how to get a pony.

00:44:06.380 --> 00:44:07.730
This is a fun example.

00:44:07.730 --> 00:44:09.430
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: And then
a single request at the end.

00:44:09.430 --> 00:44:10.540
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
A single request.

00:44:10.540 --> 00:44:11.460
This is a great example.

00:44:11.460 --> 00:44:14.080
But I would like to disclaim,
once again, that it doesn't

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:16.492
work for insane things.

00:44:16.492 --> 00:44:16.860
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Right.

00:44:16.860 --> 00:44:18.890
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: It doesn't
work for getting a pony.

00:44:18.890 --> 00:44:22.020
It doesn't work for getting
Ford to buy your new laser

00:44:22.020 --> 00:44:23.250
windshield wiper idea.

00:44:23.250 --> 00:44:24.800
And it's not gonna
get you a meeting

00:44:24.800 --> 00:44:26.060
with the CEO of Amazon.

00:44:26.060 --> 00:44:26.336
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: No.

00:44:26.336 --> 00:44:28.340
But it did work one
time when you were

00:44:28.340 --> 00:44:29.680
working for Apple, before--

00:44:29.680 --> 00:44:29.880
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:44:29.880 --> 00:44:30.710
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: --you
got to Google.

00:44:30.710 --> 00:44:32.920
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: So, I've been
refining this since first

00:44:32.920 --> 00:44:34.690
a version of this
worked for me.

00:44:34.690 --> 00:44:36.520
I was at Apple about--

00:44:36.520 --> 00:44:37.460
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
10 years ago?

00:44:37.460 --> 00:44:38.450
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
11 years ago.

00:44:38.450 --> 00:44:41.450
And I'd bought my mom one of
those big strawberry iMacs.

00:44:41.450 --> 00:44:43.080
It turned out it was
a lemon iMac.

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:44.310
And it just kept failing.

00:44:44.310 --> 00:44:46.150
And it spent more time in
the shop than ever.

00:44:46.150 --> 00:44:48.590
And I was super mad and
super frustrated.

00:44:48.590 --> 00:44:51.340
And somebody was like,
hey, Steve's email is

00:44:51.340 --> 00:44:53.140
sjobs@apple.com.

00:44:53.140 --> 00:44:53.380
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Just mail Steve.

00:44:53.380 --> 00:44:53.843
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Oh, great.

00:44:53.843 --> 00:44:54.770
Oh my God.

00:44:54.770 --> 00:44:55.820
And I just like started
ranting.

00:44:55.820 --> 00:44:57.770
My mom got this computer and
she works at the school and

00:44:57.770 --> 00:44:59.790
she did this and she did
that and she rebooted.

00:44:59.790 --> 00:45:03.640
And then, you know, like,
it was like 3,000 words.

00:45:03.640 --> 00:45:07.540
And this very wise guy I worked
with said, look, you're

00:45:07.540 --> 00:45:08.750
just wasting your time.

00:45:08.750 --> 00:45:10.690
He's like, make it short--

00:45:10.690 --> 00:45:11.310
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
Really short.

00:45:11.310 --> 00:45:12.560
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Really short
and a call to action.

00:45:12.560 --> 00:45:16.320
So, I made it really short, as
short as I could, which was

00:45:16.320 --> 00:45:17.520
still too long.

00:45:17.520 --> 00:45:20.060
And then I said, look, basically
I just want to

00:45:20.060 --> 00:45:22.230
resolve this so my mom
doesn't have this

00:45:22.230 --> 00:45:25.210
crappy, broken computer.

00:45:25.210 --> 00:45:26.100
Because I feel bad.

00:45:26.100 --> 00:45:26.750
I work at Apple.

00:45:26.750 --> 00:45:27.520
I'm trying to defend it.

00:45:27.520 --> 00:45:28.810
And she's telling all
her friends she's

00:45:28.810 --> 00:45:30.990
got this busted computer.

00:45:30.990 --> 00:45:34.050
And about 15 hours later I got
a call from somebody who

00:45:34.050 --> 00:45:34.950
worked for Steve
and said, hey--

00:45:34.950 --> 00:45:35.182
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:

00:45:35.182 --> 00:45:36.280
Administrative assistant, perhaps.

00:45:36.280 --> 00:45:36.530
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: No.

00:45:36.530 --> 00:45:36.810
It wasn't.

00:45:36.810 --> 00:45:37.470
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: No, OK.

00:45:37.470 --> 00:45:39.840
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Someone in
corporate executive relations,

00:45:39.840 --> 00:45:41.960
which is an assistant
of sorts.

00:45:41.960 --> 00:45:45.740
And a week later, my
mom had a new Mac.

00:45:45.740 --> 00:45:49.320
And we've refined this,
and we've tried

00:45:49.320 --> 00:45:50.010
this over the years.

00:45:50.010 --> 00:45:51.910
And the shorter you go-- and
when I say three bullet

00:45:51.910 --> 00:45:56.710
points, I mean, three 80
character bullet points.

00:45:56.710 --> 00:45:58.290
You can't just keep
going under this

00:45:58.290 --> 00:45:59.560
line wrap stuff, right.

00:45:59.560 --> 00:46:01.670
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Now,
sometimes you can

00:46:01.670 --> 00:46:03.200
make links to other--

00:46:03.200 --> 00:46:05.510
like, if you want more detail,
if they're really think

00:46:05.510 --> 00:46:08.190
they're gonna need background,
you can put a hyperlink in

00:46:08.190 --> 00:46:10.510
there or draw a line and say,
you know, detail is

00:46:10.510 --> 00:46:12.110
below if you care.

00:46:12.110 --> 00:46:14.040
But as long as the top
can be parsed in 10

00:46:14.040 --> 00:46:15.090
seconds, you're set.

00:46:15.090 --> 00:46:15.410
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Right.

00:46:15.410 --> 00:46:15.570
So.

00:46:15.570 --> 00:46:16.290
Yeah, sometimes I'll do that.

00:46:16.290 --> 00:46:20.130
I'll put at the top brief
summary and then long boring,

00:46:20.130 --> 00:46:20.945
long-winded rant--

00:46:20.945 --> 00:46:22.080
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
TLD [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:22.080 --> 00:46:24.420
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: --after your
signature and everything.

00:46:24.420 --> 00:46:28.000
But the fact of the matter is
that executives usually, if

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:30.980
they can wave a magic wand and
have someone that works for

00:46:30.980 --> 00:46:33.710
them right some wrong--

00:46:33.710 --> 00:46:34.110
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
They love that.

00:46:34.110 --> 00:46:34.290
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:34.290 --> 00:46:35.430
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: They
want to do good.

00:46:35.430 --> 00:46:36.950
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: That is the
best feeling in the world.

00:46:36.950 --> 00:46:38.730
They feel like Superman
or Wonder Woman.

00:46:38.730 --> 00:46:40.190
They're like, let's
make this happen.

00:46:40.190 --> 00:46:41.260
This is 10 seconds of my time.

00:46:41.260 --> 00:46:42.280
I forward an email.

00:46:42.280 --> 00:46:44.460
But if they can't parse it,
they're just gonna, yeah,

00:46:44.460 --> 00:46:45.220
delete it and get rid of it.

00:46:45.220 --> 00:46:46.910
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So give
them a chance to be awesome.

00:46:46.910 --> 00:46:48.170
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Super
valuable trick.

00:46:48.170 --> 00:46:50.100
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: So what
happens if you're in a bad

00:46:50.100 --> 00:46:53.430
company and you try all these
things, nothing is--

00:46:53.430 --> 00:46:55.100
things still are horrible.

00:46:55.100 --> 00:46:57.277
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Well, you
go to Plan B, right.

00:46:57.277 --> 00:47:00.100
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Plan
B. What is Plan B?

00:47:00.100 --> 00:47:01.670
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: So, we're
gonna talk about Plan B. It

00:47:01.670 --> 00:47:03.670
takes a little bit of time,
but we've got another 45

00:47:03.670 --> 00:47:06.800
minutes here.

00:47:06.800 --> 00:47:13.200
This is Plan B. Plan B is get
the hell out of there.

00:47:13.200 --> 00:47:13.850
Now--

00:47:13.850 --> 00:47:14.530
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: A
lot of people don't

00:47:14.530 --> 00:47:15.425
consider this option.

00:47:15.425 --> 00:47:16.600
That's just funny to me.

00:47:16.600 --> 00:47:18.620
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Now, we say
this with a little tongue in

00:47:18.620 --> 00:47:21.170
cheek, and we're trying to
be a little funny here.

00:47:21.170 --> 00:47:24.080
But we've been giving these
talks since 2007 now--

00:47:24.080 --> 00:47:26.150
2006, technically, I guess.

00:47:26.150 --> 00:47:29.620
And after these talks, every
year someone comes up to us

00:47:29.620 --> 00:47:32.500
and says, you know, all that
stuff you said, it is great.

00:47:32.500 --> 00:47:34.660
But I tried this and I've done
that and I've done that.

00:47:34.660 --> 00:47:36.820
I just can't make anything
happen in my company.

00:47:36.820 --> 00:47:39.970
And last year at IO, this guy
