First question.

00:51:28.560 --> 00:51:29.370
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Hello.

00:51:29.370 --> 00:51:31.640
MALE SPEAKER: Good afternoon.

00:51:31.640 --> 00:51:33.240
A little quick background.

00:51:33.240 --> 00:51:35.360
I work a Fortune 10 company.

00:51:35.360 --> 00:51:37.460
It has a half a million
employees.

00:51:37.460 --> 00:51:37.890
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
All right.

00:51:37.890 --> 00:51:40.360
MALE SPEAKER: And one of the
big things that we do is--

00:51:40.360 --> 00:51:43.900
like you said, perception is
9/10, and it's almost 10/10 in

00:51:43.900 --> 00:51:44.860
some points.

00:51:44.860 --> 00:51:50.180
And I've seen very technical
engineers work up the ladder

00:51:50.180 --> 00:51:52.250
through hard work and a lot
of perception because they

00:51:52.250 --> 00:51:54.150
understood the climate
very well.

00:51:54.150 --> 00:51:57.430
But then when they got to a
certain level, they began to

00:51:57.430 --> 00:51:59.710
lose some of that thing that
made them magical.

00:51:59.710 --> 00:52:02.760
Having the technical people
in the top level still be

00:52:02.760 --> 00:52:04.850
technical and still understand,
they get lost in

00:52:04.850 --> 00:52:08.030
spreadsheets and finance
records and whatnot.

00:52:08.030 --> 00:52:10.930
So you being technical
managers, how

00:52:10.930 --> 00:52:13.320
did you keep that?

00:52:13.320 --> 00:52:15.110
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: I think to
some degree, we're lucky at

00:52:15.110 --> 00:52:17.350
Google, which is a rare thing.

00:52:17.350 --> 00:52:18.970
They actually have two different
ladders, one for

00:52:18.970 --> 00:52:21.460
engineering and one for
engineering management.

00:52:21.460 --> 00:52:22.780
And they do not cross
the ladders.

00:52:22.780 --> 00:52:25.430
And they never force anyone
to move from one ladder to

00:52:25.430 --> 00:52:26.470
another, which is unusual.

00:52:26.470 --> 00:52:30.170
Typically, in a usual company,
the best engineer climbs up

00:52:30.170 --> 00:52:30.570
the ladder.

00:52:30.570 --> 00:52:33.250
And then in order to advance,
they have to become a manager.

00:52:33.250 --> 00:52:33.720
And now you've--

00:52:33.720 --> 00:52:34.030
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Which
is a terrible idea.

00:52:34.030 --> 00:52:35.710
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: --lost the
world's best engineer, and

00:52:35.710 --> 00:52:37.190
you've gained the world's
worst manager.

00:52:37.190 --> 00:52:39.550
It's awful.

00:52:39.550 --> 00:52:42.050
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: And then that
engineer usually leaves.

00:52:42.050 --> 00:52:43.120
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Yeah.

00:52:43.120 --> 00:52:44.360
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: I think
we're immune from that a

00:52:44.360 --> 00:52:45.470
little bit.

00:52:45.470 --> 00:52:47.620
But I think there's always
some element of it.

00:52:47.620 --> 00:52:49.160
And to some extent, you
can push it off.

00:52:49.160 --> 00:52:51.730
To some extent, you can
navigate around it.

00:52:51.730 --> 00:52:53.040
But it's very tricky.

00:52:53.040 --> 00:52:53.610
It really is.

00:52:53.610 --> 00:52:55.510
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: That's an
argument for focusing on

00:52:55.510 --> 00:52:59.200
social skills explicitly and
political navigation, not just

00:52:59.200 --> 00:53:01.650
relying on your technical
expertise and hoping for a

00:53:01.650 --> 00:53:03.190
meritocracy.

00:53:03.190 --> 00:53:06.920
I mean, it's an argument, I
suppose, that something they

00:53:06.920 --> 00:53:10.220
need to think about and focus
on as an actual activity.

00:53:10.220 --> 00:53:11.200
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

