00:53:37.810 --> 00:53:39.330
the darn time or--?

00:53:39.330 --> 00:53:42.010
MALE SPEAKER: Balancing the
travel, not going stir crazy,

00:53:42.010 --> 00:53:44.134
staying connected.

00:53:44.134 --> 00:53:44.970
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: That's
interesting.

00:53:44.970 --> 00:53:46.590
MALE SPEAKER: You guys are
familiar with this challenge.

00:53:46.590 --> 00:53:48.890
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well, yeah,
we about this in the

00:53:48.890 --> 00:53:50.470
book a little bit.

00:53:50.470 --> 00:53:52.690
One of the things that we
find really useful--

00:53:52.690 --> 00:53:55.340
I mean, the reason a lot of
companies like Google, for

00:53:55.340 --> 00:53:58.450
example, is they like people to
be geographically centered

00:53:58.450 --> 00:54:00.960
in one place because there's
so much value in

00:54:00.960 --> 00:54:02.330
face time, in having--

00:54:02.330 --> 00:54:04.900
just being able to swivel around
in your chair and ask

00:54:04.900 --> 00:54:08.550
the right person right next to
you a question as opposed to

00:54:08.550 --> 00:54:09.870
sending them an email
or getting on

00:54:09.870 --> 00:54:11.020
the phone or whatever.

00:54:11.020 --> 00:54:13.200
You want the friction to
be as low as possible.

00:54:13.200 --> 00:54:16.100
One way we have found working
on distributed teams-- we've

00:54:16.100 --> 00:54:17.420
been in that situation--

00:54:17.420 --> 00:54:21.850
is to actually have, like, a
continuous chatroom, like IRC

00:54:21.850 --> 00:54:22.150
in particular.

00:54:22.150 --> 00:54:23.150
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: One
of my teams has

00:54:23.150 --> 00:54:25.695
a Chromebook actually--

00:54:25.695 --> 00:54:26.820
talk about IRC first,
then we'll go on.

00:54:26.820 --> 00:54:29.100
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: Well, IRC,
right-- for those people

00:54:29.100 --> 00:54:31.280
who remember what it is--

00:54:31.280 --> 00:54:33.910
it's an actual group chat system
designed for group

00:54:33.910 --> 00:54:38.660
chat, not IM with some party
feature stapled on.

00:54:38.660 --> 00:54:41.260
It's noticeably different.

00:54:41.260 --> 00:54:44.740
Everybody would literally just
hang out in an IRC chat room

00:54:44.740 --> 00:54:47.140
all day long, corner of their
screen dedicated to it.

00:54:47.140 --> 00:54:48.720
And that became--

00:54:48.720 --> 00:54:50.750
for distributed team working in
three different offices--

00:54:50.750 --> 00:54:53.700
that became our substitute sit
in a circle, swivel all our

00:54:53.700 --> 00:54:55.210
chairs around to talk
to each other.

00:54:55.210 --> 00:54:57.070
You could fire a question
in there any time.

00:54:57.070 --> 00:54:58.020
Everybody would see it.

00:54:58.020 --> 00:54:59.230
Everybody would reply.

00:54:59.230 --> 00:55:01.710
And it creates, partially, that
allusion of being in the

00:55:01.710 --> 00:55:02.510
same room with everybody.

00:55:02.510 --> 00:55:03.510
It really helps.

00:55:03.510 --> 00:55:05.470
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: One of my
teams, actually, they use a

00:55:05.470 --> 00:55:06.120
lot of chat.

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:08.040
But I gave them a Chromebook.

00:55:08.040 --> 00:55:11.660
And they set it up between
two of the engineers.

00:55:11.660 --> 00:55:16.630
And VC Chromebook to the other
engineer in the remote office.

00:55:16.630 --> 00:55:19.770
And they had that up pretty much
half the day or so as a

00:55:19.770 --> 00:55:21.550
way to just quickly grab
a question or--

00:55:21.550 --> 00:55:23.060
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN: It is
strange to just see a floating

00:55:23.060 --> 00:55:24.940
head in the middle
of a bullpen.

00:55:24.940 --> 00:55:26.280
Like, is that your
other teammate?

00:55:26.280 --> 00:55:27.460
BRYAN FITZPATRICK: When people
are coding, they look very

00:55:27.460 --> 00:55:29.600
angry most of the time.

00:55:29.600 --> 00:55:34.270
But you have to use everything
in your power to do that.

00:55:34.270 --> 00:55:36.890
And the fact of the matter is
is that the people, the

00:55:36.890 --> 00:55:39.260
engineers who are in the remote
office-- and having

00:55:39.260 --> 00:55:41.780
been in the remote office
for many, many years--

00:55:41.780 --> 00:55:43.050
it takes more work.

00:55:43.050 --> 00:55:45.500
It takes more effort to get
where you're going.

00:55:45.500 --> 00:55:47.500
And the advantage of
that is you get to

00:55:47.500 --> 00:55:48.640
live where you want.

00:55:48.640 --> 00:55:49.210
So--

00:55:49.210 --> 00:55:49.820
BEN COLLINS-SUSSMAN:
It's a tradeoff.

00:55:49.820 --> 00:55:50.500
BRYAN FITZPATRICK:
It's a tradeoff.

